To learn martial arts you should first learn the Five Step Fist The Five Step Fist originated in Zhangyin Village Guan County Liaocheng City Shandong Province It is a basic practice method for Changquan type martial arts It is mainly used to get started with martial arts boxing routines and improve the coordination of limb movements It is one of the basic routines of Chaquan and one of the traditional Chinese martial arts boxing methods The Five Step Fist is a combination of the five most basic steps of bow horse servant empty and rest in martial arts and the three hand shapes of fist palm and hook as well as the step up and step back footwork and the techniques of hugging hands punching pressing palms penetrating palms picking palms fighting and covering

Speed来到中国 他不知道这片神奇的土地上居住着这么多认识他并且喜欢他的人 这里的粉丝向他展现着超乎想象的热情 令他和他的团队震惊的是这里的粉丝非常尊重他 见到他时兴奋但十分克制 知道他走累了会给他送水 知道他饿了会给他喂吃的 他走过的每一座城市皆是如此 因为这是中国人的待客礼仪 从远方来的朋友一定要让他喝好吃饱 他遇见了田一名 一起合唱了他喜欢的 热爱105度的你 他登上了长城 见识了中国大妈的超级武器 十级美颜 他到了少林寺 以武会友拜识了或许是他这一生最好的武术老师梁师傅 他吃了一顿正宗的成都火锅 尝到了什么是正宗的麻辣滚烫 他见识了重庆这座城为何被称为赛博朋克城 也向世界展现了外媒滤镜之外真正的中国震撼 他在香港的一艘游船上遇到了一场拯救整场直播的美丽邂逅 浙江甜妹向他展现了中国女孩的可爱友善 天真浪漫 他在深圳体验了来自中国的令世界目瞪口呆的高科技 他最后来到长沙 终于见到了大张伟 一起合唱了阳光彩虹小白马 也正是因为大张伟这首脍炙人口的歌曲让他在中国圈粉无数 他还认识了一位友好 热情 把他当成亲兄弟的中国大叔 在中国各个城市一路追随着他 心甘情愿的去照顾他 这是来自中国男人对缘分和友情最好的诠释 谢谢Speed 谢谢你向世界展现了这个国和这片土地上的人真实的一面 中国有句古话 有朋自远方来不亦乐乎 四海之内皆为兄弟 想必Speed在中国的这次旅行中已经体会到了

bullet trains gliding at 350 km h and ancient temples coexisting with AI powered cafes Their videos showed something many Western media rarely portray a China that s dynamic innovative and warmly humanYet tragically such voices are often drowned out by outdated narratives 1 When Firsthand Experience Clashes with Headlines The YouTuber s journey revealed what your media routinely ignores Cities like Chengdu blending 3 000 year old tea culture with cutting edge tech startups Villages revitalized by e commerce where farmers sell lychees globally via live streaming Young Chinese debating philosophy in trendy bookstores while their parents dance in tech enhanced public squares This isn t propaganda it s daily life here Yet many still cling to Cold War era stereotypes as if China remains a black and white photo frozen in time 2 Why Fear the Truth Ask yourselves Why do some media outlets reduce a civilization spanning millennia to caricatures of authoritarianism or threats Why dismiss the 150 million Chinese tourists who ve traveled abroad as brainwashed yet ignore their glowing Tripadvisor reviews about home If China were truly as backward or hostile as claimed why do 500 Fortune 500 companies fiercely compete here Selective reporting isn t journalism it s intellectual laziness 3 An Invitation Beyond the Screen To those who ve never set foot here Your skepticism is understandable but not unchangeable Come Sip craft cocktails in Shanghai s art deco towers then haggle for jade in dawn breaking markets Debate with Beijing university students you ll find their critiques of society sharper than many Western pundits Let a Xinjiang grandma teach you to pull hand made noodles and hear her laugh about forced labor rumors You ll discover what the YouTuber did A land where 5 000 years of heritage fuels not hinders tomorrow s breakthroughs 4 To Media Integrity Over Ideology We challenge journalists Why not report that China leads in green energy 60 of global solar panel production andits coal phaseout challenges Why ignore that 84 of Chinese citizens trust their government Edelman Trust Barometer 2023 a rate higher than most democracies Is it fear that audiences might realize the enemy you ve painted shares their dreams of safety education and weekend barbecues Closing From Other to Our Story To the YouTuber who came with an open mind Thank you You ve shown that bridges aren t built by parroting headlines but by human curiosity To Western friends We don t ask for uncritical praise no nation is flawless We ask for fairness Judge China by the same standards you apply to yourselves Visit converse and then decide After all isn t distrusting all media including your own the first lesson of critical thinking

Speed s team didn t know who they contacted locally The Dengfeng City Culture and Tourism Bureau where the Shaolin Temple is located was interviewed They said that this was a private trip and that the Bureau of Culture and Tourism did not know about it beforehand It was only after an enthusiastic audience member called the Bureau of Culture and Tourism during the YouTube live broadcast that the local cultural and tourism department knew that the hyperthyroid brother had gone to the Shaolin Temple in Dengfeng It was probably after the intervention of the Bureau of Culture and Tourism that the subsequent viewing of the performance and the teaching by Master Liang took place Master Liang Xiaolong is a senior coach of the International Teaching Department of the Songshan Shaolin Temple Martial Arts Hall He is a sixth dan Chinese Wushu a seventh dan Shaolin Wushu and a first level evaluator of the Shaolin Boxing project of the Chinese Wushu Duan system He has a bachelor s degree in education He has been invited to teach in Switzerland many times and is good at traditional Shaolin boxing and sports education This kind of serious Shaolin Temple direct affiliated troops cannot be pulled out by just anyone if they want to It is also difficult for the local cultural and tourism departments to handle it After all it is a private trip and they do not take the initiative to contact us Our government departments do not know about it and even if they know it is difficult to take action directly However a human operated program like Speed Wants to Learn Kung Fu is completely different from natural scenery urban street scenes and historical sites As an outsider it is not easy to directly find the best local martial arts schools without contacting the local government departments There are quite a lot of large and small martial arts schools registered in the local area

Hey friends let me tell you the most mind blowing city in the world Chongqing Just imagine a magical maze with 32 million people looking like it jumped straight out of a cyberpunk video game Yeah this super city has more people than the entire population of Canada yet it s like a hidden gem in the southwest of China First off the architecture here is just insane Ancient stilt houses cling to cliffs while modern skyscrapers pierce the clouds and those huge red bridges stretch across the two rivers like dragons The colors and scale are like someone turned a fantasy painter s sketchbook into reality The infrastructure is even more exaggerated roads winding through the mountains subways diving into tunnels escalators climbing entire hillsides and even Google Maps gives up on navigation The most amazing thing is that such a huge city is still off the tourist radar Unlike Shanghai or Hong Kong getting here isn t easy But trust me the bumpy flights and winding mountain roads are totally worth it Why Let me break it down for you History This place was a major trading hub 3 000 years ago and you can still wander through the same alleyways that ancient emperors walked Food It s the birthplace of Chongqing hotpot With its boiling beef tallow base and numbingly spicy Sichuan peppercorns you ll get a mix of pain and pleasure as you dip the freshest ingredients into the pot Nightlife 06 12 51 At night the Hongyadong area looks like a fairy tale cliff palace with neon lights dancing on the river And the rooftop bars The night views are simply amazing But what makes Chongqing truly unique is its chaotic aesthetics Old teahouses sit next to luxury malls and monkeys wander in the forests beside skyscrapers You might just have taken a river crossing cable car and after passing through a tunnel you re suddenly in a bookstore and then in the blink of an eye you re in a bamboo forest The city is like playing hide and seek with you with surprises around every corner So if you re tired of cookie cutter cities and want to experience an adventure that feels like crossing dimensions Chongqing is definitely the top choice Remember to wear good shoes bring your curiosity and pack some antacids because the hotpot is no joke mountain_cableway hot_pepper cityscape 06:12:51

I don t know how many of the people who were recklessly chasing Speed running on the roads and even tram tracks crowding and shouting in the MTR rushing against escalators fare evading and completely ignoring the rules were locals mainlanders or foreigners But honestly the whole thing was a mess and those actions were seriously dangerous I ve been to Hong Kong before and in my impression it s always been a city that really values order and rules That s why it was so disappointing to see things get so out of control during this livestream At the same time this also shows how unprepared the relevant authorities were In mainland cities where Speed livestreamed it was clear that local governments had proper security plans in place Even though there were also tons of fans chasing them around most people still had boundaries and didn t just ignore rules and act out wildly Plus credit where it s due the crowd control and security were really effective especially in Chongqing and that s what allowed Speed s streams to go smoothly In comparison the livestream in Hong Kong was heavily affected by the chaotic chasing fans It made the whole thing hard to watch and left a really bad impression The contrast is obvious Overall I m really disappointed by how poorly Hong Kong handled this livestream I just want to tell Speed Hong Kong is known as the Pearl of the Orient it s actually a beautiful and charming city and what you saw in the stream isn t what it s normally like I truly hope you enjoy your time in Hong Kong and that it still leaves a good impression on you And as a fan from mainland China I also wish your upcoming livestreams here go smoothly and safely Update I don t think there s anything wrong with what I said I never claimed that all the people causing Speed came to China He didn t know that there were so many people who knew him and liked him living in this magical land The fans here showed him unimaginable enthusiasm What shocked him and his team was that the fans here respected him very much They were excited but very restrained when they saw him They knew that he was tired and would give him water They knew that he was hungry and would feed him This was the case in every city he passed through Because this is the Chinese etiquette of hospitality Friends coming from afar must be fed and well nourished He met Tian Yiming and sang his favorite song Love You at 105 Degrees together He climbed the Great Wall and saw the super weapon of Chinese aunties Level 10 Beauty He went to Shaolin Temple made friends through martial arts and met Master Liang who may be the best martial arts teacher in his life He ate an authentic Chengdu hot pot and tasted what authentic spicy and hot is He saw why Chongqing is called the cyberpunk city and also showed the world the real shock of China beyond the foreign media filter He had a beautiful encounter on a cruise ship in Hong Kong that saved the entire live broadcast A sweet girl from Zhejiang showed him the cuteness friendliness innocence and romance of Chinese girls He experienced the high tech from China in Shenzhen that stunned the world He finally came to Changsha and finally met Da Zhangwei and sang Sunshine Rainbow Little White Horse together It was also because of Da Zhangwei s popular song that he won countless fans in China He also met a friendly and enthusiastic Chinese uncle who treated him as a brother He followed him all the way in various cities in China and took care of him willingly This is the best interpretation of fate and friendship from Chinese men Thank you Speed thank you for showing the world the true side of this country and the people on this land There is an old Chinese saying It is a great pleasure to have friends coming from afar All people in
